  superstition which made them the easy prey of their unscrupulous
  clergy and left them wholly sensual and stupid as animals, without
  the animals' instinctive joy of life and fearlessness of the morrow,
  with no ambitions for themselves or the children who turned to curse
  them for having brought them into such a world; with no time to dream
  or love, no time for the tenderness which makes life, life indeed.
  they toiled for a few cruel years because they feared to die,
  and died because they feared to live.
  Such were the people Turgot was sent to redeem.

